article.description: Katie Smith scored 22 points and Svetlana Abrosimova added 20 as the Minnesota Lynx held off the Sacramento Monarchs 72-63 Tuesday night to win their first home game of the season.
article.headline: Smith scores 22 for Lynx; Abrosimova adds 20
article.linkText: Lynx hold off Monarchs to win first home game
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS -- Katie Smith scored 22 points and Svetlana Abrosimova added 20 as the Minnesota Lynx held off the Sacramento Monarchs 72-63 Tuesday night to win their first home game of the season. Abrosimova shot 3-of-3 from 3-point range and Smith made seven free throws in the final three minutes as the Lynx (3-3) stopped a late Sacramento rally. ``Their big players always step up,'' Monarchs head coach Maura McHugh said. ``Smith didn't shoot well, but she got to the line and got the job done. That makes it much easier for their other players.'' Smith shot just 4-of-14 from the field, but made up for it with an outstanding night at the foul line, going 13-for-15. ``This was probably her worst shooting night all year, but her attack mentality got her to the line,'' Lynx coach Brian Agler said of Smith. ``Overall that was probably one of the most composed games we've played.'' Kedra Holland-Corn scored 17 for the Monarchs (0-4). Minnesota led by as many as 18 in the second half, but the Monarchs pulled within eight when Holland-Corn hit a 3-pointer with 3:20 to play. After Minnesota scored, Holland-Corn hit a jumper with under a minute left to again pull the Monarchs within eight, but they would get no closer. Lynn Pride and Tamika Williams each had seven rebounds to lead the Lynx, while Hamchetou Maiga had seven for the Monarchs. ``We just don't play 40 minutes of consistent basketball,'' said Sacramento's Ticha Penicheriro, who scored 16. ``We seem to play consistently for only 10 or 15 minutes a game, which is why we're 0-4.''

Game notes
Minnesota, which made 19 of 24 free throws, entered shooting a league-worst 59.4 percent from the line this season. ... Sacramento's 0-4 start marks the club's first four-game losing streak since their inaugural season in 1998 ... When the Lynx starting lineup for Tuesday's game was introduced, a handful of fans behind the Minnesota bench chanted, ``Betty, Betty, Betty,'' for guard Betty Lennox, who was traded to Miami earlier in the day. Lennox, the WNBA rookie of the year in 2000, averaged 6.2 points and 3.2 rebounds in five games for the Lynx this season. She was suspended Monday for one game without pay and fined $500 by the league for leaving the bench during a game against Los Angeles on Saturday.
